Greig is a puzzle mob.<br>
<br>
Figuring him out is 90% of the battle... once you know, and can execute the strat he is terribly easy.<br>
<br>
I know this is small comfort if you are looking for more info, but that 'more info' is basically handing him over.  Sit down with your braintrust and experiment.  Figuring out these kinds of mobs are among the best experiences in the game. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ueasirok.showPublicProfile?language=EN>easirok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/30/02 9:36:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousethebackroomsecretsspoilers.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11665.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Anyone know a strategy to take down Grieg?</span><hr size=1> There is probably a dozen ways to kill him, all with their own merits and flaws.<br>
<br>
After a few tries and a lot of thinking about how to deal with his annoying AEs, this is what we do (and it always works now):<br>
<br>
Clerics make balanced groups. Key is to have healing distributed among the melee. Casters can all group together. If they are paying attention, they wont take damage.<br>
<br>
Coming in from the portal room, go through the door, and up the stairs, then it makes a right turn. We place our clerics and casters there on the right wall to sheild them from AE.<br>
<br>
Coming in from the portal room, next to the door, on the right hand side, in the hallway, before the first flight of steps. This is where ALL melee wait (no exceptions).<br>
<br>
There is not really a MT. You can designate one and he can taunt his heart out, it just dont end up with that one tanking. Treat all melee as shifting MTs, heal whomever needs it. Hence the spreading of your healing ability to every group. Clerics also can target group members with F2-F6 a lot easier than using /target.<br>
<br>
Greig is indifferent/dubious until aggroed. His 4 guards are fast respawn - 10 minutes or less. Just pull the guards as fast as you can kill them... you dont want an add during the fight as it just complicates an already annoying fight.<br>
<br>
Use a shadowknight to snare pull him (high aggro) down the steps, past the casters (they will all suffer heart attacks - but the SK should have sufficient aggro that greig ignores them), and stop right before the door, directly next to the melee. If the SK can get away with it, FD right away so the melee can get him turned towards them.<br>
<br>
Then all melee just start beating the piss out of greig. He will be placed with back against one wall next to door, melee with back against the opposite hallway wall.<br>
<br>
Your rogues will need to leave their ego at the door for this one, because nobody will be standing behind greig (at least not for long).<br>
<br>
He has two AEs and one single-target attack. His melee is a joke - it ranks equal or lower than his guards, especially once slowed.<br>
<br>
The single-target attack is a blindness, not sure if its got Curse or Poison or Disease counters, but if this positioning strategy is used, it wont matter since you will always be facing him and never out of range.<br>
<br>
The first AE is &quot;Gravel Rain&quot;, easily resistable snare. However, this fight lasts long enough that it WILL eventually hit you, and combined with the other AE and blindness can really screw up your melee. Even more annoying is the snare will last for a very long time and in some cases (has happened to me) it will still be on you even after death. Could not find any way to cure it, just had to wait it out or hope /duel clears it.<br>
<br>
The other AE is a strange knockback/stun. Its resistable, but VERY hard to resist (magic based). If you resist more than one or two the whole fight, then you are a very lucky person. The knockback portion of this effect kicks everyone within greig's line of sight to DIRECTLY where he is facing, and you wont stop until you hit a wall (yay all melee get pinned in a corner, unable to move from the pile-up). The stun portion affects you once you land, and is a good 6-8 seconds long. He procs this AE about every 15 or so seconds as best I can tell.<br>
<br>
If your melee are positioned as I mention, across a hallway from him, he will always be facing them, and they will never get thrown out of melee range from the knockback (backs are to the wall already). As soon as the stun wears off, all melee will be able to resume fighting, without worry about the snare that will inevitably hit them or the blindness. Have a melee call out the *stun* AEs, so your casters can step out for nukes between them. Healers are always protected from AE by the corner and should never be out of range. If he somehow does manage to go after your casters, a simple Stun cast by a paladin will easily grab his attention and you can pull him back down to where you want him.<br>
<br>
Last thing.... when he close to death make SURE he is not tight against a wall. Even if you have to prolong the final moments of the fight, pull him out into the middle of the hallway for the killing blow. If he dies too close to a wall, the human version (one with loot) will poof when it dies, and that will just make everyone mad.<br>
